## 1. The Anatomy of the Dual-Zone Structure

Under the Theory of Infinite Relativity (TIR), an elementary particle like an electron is never exclusively a wave or a particle. It is a permanent, localized dual-zone architecture:

* **The Core (The Particle Aspect):** A hyper-dense, high-torque central rotational stall where the tangential velocity has reached the medium's structural propagation threshold ($v_\theta \rightarrow c$).
* **The Field (The Wave Aspect):** A vast, low-torque outer boundary field ($r$) radiating outward across the underlying medium layer.

When an electron is fired at a macro-scale double-slit apparatus, the physical dimensions of the components dictate the interaction. The localized high-torque core is spatially constrained and can only pass through **one** slit. Concurrently, its extended low-torque outer field spans a wide enough spatial footprint to pass through **both** slits simultaneously.

As the outer field navigates the slits, it deforms the underlying medium, carving a localized hydrodynamic diffraction pattern of alternating high- and low-acceleration gradients ahead of the particle. The trailing core is then mechanically steered along the path of least resistance generated by its own leading field.

