## 2. Wavelength as Geometric Helical Pitch

The classical de Broglie wavelength ($\lambda$) is stripped of its probabilistic interpretation and redefined as a literal spatial metric: **the Helical Pitch ($\lambda_{\text{geom}}$)**.

As a free loop propagates through space, its total velocity vector splits orthogonally between its internal tangential spin ($v_\theta = c$) and its forward radial propagation velocity ($v_r$):

$$v^2 = c^2 + v_r^2$$

The spatial wavelength is the precise forward radial distance the particle travels during one complete internal orbital period ($T = 2\pi r^{3/2}$):

$$\lambda_{\text{geom}} = v_r \cdot T = 2\pi v_r r^{3/2}$$

Because the particle's internal clock is fixed by its core geometric mass ($r = M_{\text{geom}}/c^2$), the trajectory of a moving electron through time traces a literal physical helix in the medium. Pumping energy into the particle alters its forward velocity ($v_r$), which compresses or elongates the physical pitch of this geometric spring.

