## 3. Dimensional Translation of Laboratory Energy

To validate TIR against real-world data, laboratory energy measured in Electron-Volts ($\text{eV}$) must be converted into the medium's native dimensional profile ($\text{meters}^5 / \text{seconds}^4$). This is achieved via the universal scaling constant $\kappa$, which incorporates the gravitational constant ($G \equiv 1$) as a dimensional bridge:

$$\kappa = G \cdot (1.602 \times 10^{-19} \text{ Joules/eV}) \approx 1.069 \times 10^{-29} \text{ m}^5\text{s}^{-4}/\text{eV}$$

The kinetic energy ($K_{\text{geom}}$) injected to fire the electron forward belongs exclusively to the radial velocity component:

$$K_{\text{geom}} = \kappa \cdot E_{\text{eV}} = \frac{1}{2} M_{\text{geom}} v_r^2$$

Isolating the forward radial velocity yields:

$$v_r = \sqrt{\frac{2 \kappa E_{\text{eV}}}{M_{\text{geom}}}}$$

Substituting $v_r$ and the structural equilibrium radius ($r^{3/2} = M_{\text{geom}}^{3/2}/c^3$) back into the wavelength equations yields the definitive **TIR Helical Pitch Formula**:

$$\lambda_{\text{geom}} = \frac{2\pi \sqrt{2 \kappa E_{\text{eV}} M_{\text{geom}}}}{c^3}$$

Plugging this directly into the classical slit intensity equation maps the exact spatial distribution of the particle hits on a detector screen at an angle $\theta$:

$$I(\theta) \propto \cos^2\left(\frac{c^3 d \sin\theta}{2 \sqrt{2 \kappa E_{\text{eV}} M_{\text{geom}}}}\right)$$

The $\cos^2$ function operates as a fluid-mechanical efficiency rating. Fringes are not probabilities; they are regions where the structural propagation threshold of the medium ($c^3$) either funnels the helical spring smoothly forward ($\cos^2 \rightarrow 1$) or generates catastrophic frictional resistance ($\cos^2 \rightarrow 0$), mechanically deflecting the core away from the coordinate.

