## 4. The Screen Interface: Boundary Resolution Dynamics

When the electron arrives at the detection screen—which consists of a highly tensioned lattice of nested atomic loops—the manifestation of a discrete "particle hit" is governed by an all-or-nothing digital threshold. Whether a localized state change occurs depends on the **Velocity Ratio ($\frac{v_\theta}{v_r}$)**, which represents the alignment of the incoming helix relative to the orbital transit time of the target atom.

The interaction splits into three strictly deterministic, scale-invariant mechanical outcomes:

### I. Sub-Threshold Core Penetration & Volumetric Shear (The Photon Emission)

When the scalar velocity ratio falls below the critical interaction threshold ($\frac{v_\theta}{v_r} < \text{Threshold}$), the forward radial velocity is too high relative to the loop's internal orbital spin. The spatial pitch of the incoming helix is too wide to satisfy the phase-matching condition within the outer harmonic shell; the loop transits the orbital domain without intersecting the bound electron's path.

Consequently, the incoming loop penetrates directly into the steep acceleration gradient ($a$) of the hyper-dense core, where $a = M_{\text{geom}}/r^2$ spikes exponentially as $r \rightarrow 10^{-15}\text{ m}$. Because total velocity is bounded ($v^2 = v_\theta^2 + v_r^2$), the loop cannot maintain its structural equilibrium equation ($r = v^2/a$) against this colossal gradient while retaining forward momentum. This forces an immediate velocity saturation lock, driving the forward radial component abruptly to zero ($v_r \rightarrow 0$).

Because the incoming loop scale lacks a resonant harmonic match with the hyper-dense core's deep sub-quantum gear layer, this sudden step-discontinuity in radial velocity ($\frac{dv_r}{dt} \rightarrow \infty$) cannot be absorbed as localized internal torque. The unabsorbed deceleration energy causes an abrupt volumetric shear deformation in the underlying medium. This localized displacement is shed outward as a transient wave excitation—a literal mechanical pluck propagating natively across the photon-scale surface layer at the boundary threshold velocity ($c$), which is macroscopically detected as a **Photon Emission**.

### II. Integer Harmonic Phase-Lock & Geometric Torque Transfer (Ionization)

When the velocity ratio exceeds the baseline threshold and matches an integer harmonic ($\frac{v_\theta}{v_r} = n$), an intersection with the target atom's outer orbital shell becomes a mechanical certainty.

If the relative algebraic sign of their tangential velocities matches ($\Delta v_\theta = v_{\text{bound}} - v_{\text{incoming}} \rightarrow 0$), the teeth of the two independent fields drop into perfect phase-alignment. The fields lock instantly. The incoming loop's forward velocity drops to zero ($v_r \rightarrow 0$), and its remaining energy forces an immediate, violent spike in the tangential spin component ($v_\theta$), dumping its cumulative geometric torque ($M_{\text{geom}}$) directly into the bound orbital loop.

This sudden torque overload destabilizes the target loop's equilibrium ($r = v^2/a$), causing it to un-moor and spin out of the atom's field entirely. The incoming loop is deflected away with depleted energy, leaving the parent atom with a permanent structural vacancy—observed macroscopically as **Ionization**.

### III. Non-Resonant Phase Mismatch & Frictional Deflection (Elastic Scattering)

If the velocity ratio exceeds the threshold but forms an irrational or counter-rotating fractional relationship ($\Delta v_\theta \rightarrow 2v$), the fields interface out of phase. The fields collide out of alignment, creating localized sub-quantum friction. A clean phase-lock cannot establish. The fields mechanically buffet and deflect off one another without triggering a structural state change, manifesting macroscopically as **Elastic Scattering** or background **Quantum Jitter**.